As Anthony wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/24/2004 at 16:32:10 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>I just started my math class and the first thing the teacher did was 
>lead us through a review of fractions, decimals, number lines, 
>integers, and percents. Most of it relatively easy, but one example 
>that she showed didn't make much sense to me and I didn't get a 
>chance to ask her about it after class. Being that most of what we 
>did that day was pretty simple I don't expect this to have that 
>difficult of an answer, but I'm curious as to how my teacher came to 
>this conclusion. What I want to know is this:
>On the overhead my teacher had drawn a number line that showed only 
>the positive integers that went all the way from zero up to five. 
>Then to the side of the number line was written 9 1/2 and you were 
>to find 9 1/2 on the number line. Then she had taken the 9 1/2 and 
>turned it into 9/2 which she then divided and got 4.5 or 4 1/2. 
>
>[Difficulty]
>What I don't understand about this problem is how she was able to 
>turn 9 1/2 into 9/2. That really doesn't make any sense to me and so 
>I would really appreciate it if you would explain it to me the steps 
>leading to such a transformation.
>
>[Thoughts]
>

Hi Anthony.

thanks for writing to the Math Forum.  I'm not sure, but perhaps
it is difference between interpreting

   9 1/2  as  nine and one-half, i.e., 9 + (1/2)

and

   (9)(1/2) = 9 x (1/2) = 9/2 = 4.5.

This is all I can think of at the moment.  

